	<h1 class="Introduction">
		Introduction:</h1>
	<p class="para_last">
		The following tables contain useful medicines and dressings that could be kept in
		a home medicine chest. All are quite cheap and are available to buy at the pharmacy.
		They are worth keeping at home for minor illnesses.</p>
	<h1 class="MediChestContents">
		Family Medicine Chest Contents:</h1>
	<table border="0" align="center" cellpadding="8" cellspacing="0" class="tabType02"
		summary="Suggestions for what to keep in your Family Medicine Chest.">
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2" class="tabheader">
				Family Medicine Chest:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC1" id="MC1"></a>General Items:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Scissors
			</td>
			<td>
				Tweezers
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Thermometer
			</td>
			<td>
				Travel Sickness Pills
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="2">
				Your Doctor's Emergency Telephone Number
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="2">
				Record of last Tetanus Vaccination
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC2" id="MC2"></a>General Pain Killers:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				For Adults
			</td>
			<td>
				E.g. Aspirin, Paracetomol, Ibuprofen.
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				For Children
			</td>
			<td>
				Paracetamol or Ibuprofen suspension.
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="2">
				Note: Never give Aspirin if under 16 years of age.
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC3" id="MC3"></a>Cuts &amp; Grazes:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Plasters
			</td>
			<td>
				Gauze Dressing
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Sticky Tape
			</td>
			<td>
				Cotton Wool
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Antiseptic Cleansing Solution
			</td>
			<td>
				Antiseptic Cream
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC4" id="MC4"></a>Sprains:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="2">
				Tubigrip or Crepe Bandage
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC5" id="MC5"></a>Eyes:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Eyebath
			</td>
			<td>
				Sterile Water or 'Optrex'
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC6" id="MC6"></a>Insect Bites &amp; Stings, Allergies &amp; Sunburn:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Antihistamine Tablets/Syrup
			</td>
			<td>
				Hydrocortisone Cream (only appropriate for over 10's)
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Insect Repellant Spray
			</td>
			<td>
				&nbsp;
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC7" id="MC7"></a>Stomach Upsets &amp; Indigestion:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Electrolyte Replacement Sachets (for dehydration)
			</td>
			<td>
				Anti-Diarrhoea Tablets (Not for Children)
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				Tablets or Liquid for indigestion - Ask the pharmacist for advice.
			</td>
			<td>
				&nbsp;
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC8" id="MC8"></a>Rashes:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="2">
				Calamine Lotion
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC9" id="MC9"></a>Cough Mixtures:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="2">
				<p>
					For dry coughs use a Simple linctus (or Simple linctus paediatric for children).
					We have many other cough mixtures available, and can advise you in-store.
				</p>
				<p>
					Soothing drinks can also be made.
				</p>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<th colspan="2">
				<a name="MC10" id="MC10"></a>Mouth Ulcer Treatments:
			</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class="noborder">
				Mouth Ulcers:
			</td>
			<td class="noborder">
				Choline Salicylate Gel (E.g. Bonjela) may help.
			</td>
		</tr>
	</table>
